Raksit: and I'm hoping to remedy this as I look at more speakers, but we can look at gender crossed by generation, so

123
00:17:07.170 --> 00:17:18.300
Raksit: here what we're looking at is that young speakers are blue, older speakers are red. So younger speakers, well younger women have the weakest H1*-H2* difference. Their curves are the closest together, but we can see that

124
00:17:18.780 --> 00:17:22.980
Raksit: for men, the difference doesn't really matter much, although the shapes of the curves are definitely different.

125
00:17:24.330 --> 00:17:31.530
Raksit: In terms of f0, what we see is that younger people have a clearer f0 different. So the blue curves are on the outside of the red curves.

126
00:17:32.070 --> 00:17:39.300
Raksit: And this is especially noticeable for younger women. So to compare the perception and production results, what we see is that

127
00:17:39.900 --> 00:17:52.980
Raksit: older men or those who rank higher on experience are the most conservative. They're the ones weighing open quotient the highest, the heaviest. And younger women or women who rank low on experience are spearheading the loss of breathiness.

128
00:17:54.120 --> 00:17:57.090
Raksit: Now there are some differences in perception and production. So, for example,

129
00:17:57.330 --> 00:18:02.250
Raksit: in perception. It's lower experience men who are the ones that rely the most on fundamental frequency

130
00:18:02.430 --> 00:18:13.530
Raksit: but in production, it's the younger women who are the ones that rely the most on fundamental frequency. So remember that younger corresponds with being lower experience. Now in perception, men are more affected by social factors

131
00:18:14.760 --> 00:18:20.280
Raksit: than women are. And what's interesting here now is the difference at the very bottom, so

132
00:18:21.030 --> 00:18:24.330
Raksit: in terms of production, we see that there's a trade off both

133
00:18:24.570 --> 00:18:31.980
Raksit: if you are younger, there's a trade off between open quotient and fundamental frequency. This corresponds with lower experience. And if you're away longer

134
00:18:32.280 --> 00:18:37.710
Raksit: then you also have a trade off between open quotient and fundamental frequency. This corresponds with being more integrated into Thai society.

135
00:18:38.160 --> 00:18:53.010
Raksit: Now in perception, though, what we see is that the trade off only occurs in the population that is low experience and also lowly integrated. But, if you are highly integrated in Thai society, you only have dulling of the breathiness cue without any trade off so

136
00:18:54.030 --> 00:19:05.550
Raksit: Let's sum up this case and explain that a little bit. Now, those who are both younger or lower experience and also those who have been away longer or are more integrated into Thai society

137
00:19:06.810 --> 00:19:15.480
Raksit: have a trade off between breathiness and fundamental frequency cues in production, but in perception, greater integration only ends up weakening the breathiness cues without the trade off.

138
00:19:16.020 --> 00:19:20.190
Raksit: Where we see the trade off is in the low experience low integration group. So let me try to maybe

139
00:19:20.700 --> 00:19:28.080
